### VIOLATIONS FOUND

**VIOLATION: MEDIUM [steps-c/step-04-report.md:88-92] Re-run tier change logic uses prose placeholders without binding `{previous_tier}` — the variable is declared in CONTEXT BOUNDARIES but never referenced in the report template body.**

The CONTEXT BOUNDARIES section (line 44) correctly declares `{previous_tier}` as available from step-01. The SUCCESS METRICS (line 132) require tier changes to be "correctly reported." However, the report template in section 2 (lines 88-92) renders the re-run blocks as:

```
{if re-run with tier change:}
  {appropriate upgrade/downgrade message from tier-rules.md}
{if re-run with same tier:}
  {same-tier message from tier-rules.md}
```

The condition `{if re-run with tier change:}` is not expressed using the declared variable `{previous_tier}`. The tier-rules.md upgrade/downgrade messages reference `{previous}` and `{current}` placeholders, but neither `{previous_tier}` nor `{calculated_tier}` is surfaced inside those conditional blocks. The executor has no machine-readable signal for what constitutes a "tier change" — it requires implicit inference rather than a defined boolean comparison. This creates ambiguity for the autonomous executor and diverges from how all other conditional logic in the workflow is written (compare step-03's explicit `{calculated_tier}` branch). The fix is to express the condition as `{if previous_tier != calculated_tier:}` and `{if previous_tier == calculated_tier:}`.

